Formal Foundations of the Agent Engineering Standard (AES)

A Mathematical Framework for Compliant, Observable, and Safe Autonomous Agents

Author: ouadi Maakoul 

---

Chapter 1: Introduction

The Agent Engineering Standard (AES) defines a unified interface for autonomous agents, mandating a lifecycle of perception, state update, planning, action, and learning. This thesis develops the mathematical foundations that underpin AES, establishing formal definitions, temporal logic specifications, and proofs of key properties. We introduce a formal model of the agent state and its transitions, define compliance via linear temporal logic (LTL) with explicit atomic propositions, and provide a rigorous treatment of certification levels. A novel graph‑theoretic formalization of blast radius is presented, together with compositional verification techniques based on assume‑guarantee reasoning. We extend the standard to handle stochastic agents via probabilistic LTL and Markov decision processes. Finally, we describe the construction of a runtime monitor, prove its correctness, and demonstrate how the specification can be machine‑checked using the Lean 4 theorem prover.

The presentation is self‑contained; we assume familiarity with basic set theory, automata theory, temporal logic, and probability.

---

Chapter 2: Related Work

The field of agent verification has seen rapid advances since 2024. This chapter situates AES against the state of the art.

2.1 Runtime Verification of LLM Agents
AgentSpec (ICSE 2026) introduces a customizable runtime enforcement framework with a rule‑based DSL for specifying safety properties of LLM agents, supporting both preventive and corrective enforcement modes. Our Bronze monitor uses LTL directly, offering a more formal foundation but lacking the natural language interface.

Pro2Guard (2025) abstracts agent behaviors into symbolic states and learns a Discrete‑Time Markov Chain (DTMC) from execution traces; at runtime, it predicts the probability of leading to undesired behaviors and intervenes before violations occur when the estimated risk exceeds a user‑defined threshold. Our work extends AES to probabilistic compliance, but Pro2Guard focuses on prediction rather than certification.

AgentGuard (2025) operates as an inspection layer that observes an agent’s raw I/O and abstracts it into formal events corresponding to transitions in a state model, then uses online learning to dynamically build and update a Markov Decision Process that formally models the agent’s emergent behavior. This is complementary: AgentGuard builds the model; AES certifies it.

The ABC Framework (2026) captures the insight that hard constraints require high‑probability guarantees of persistent compliance, while soft constraints require high‑probability guarantees of recoverable compliance. This directly inspired our Probabilistic Bronze tier.

2.2 Formal Methods for Multi‑Agent Systems
Classical works on temporal logic and model checking (Pnueli 1977; Baier & Katoen 2008) provide the foundation. Recent advances in assume‑guarantee reasoning for multi‑agent systems (Henzinger et al. 1994; Alur & Henzinger 1996) have been extended to quantitative assume‑guarantee contracts, which we adapt to AES Gold.

2.3 Mechanized Verification
Lean 4 has been used to verify properties of concurrent and distributed systems, but its application to agent lifecycle compliance is novel. We build on the standard library for LTL and automata to provide a machine‑checked proof of Bronze monitor invariants.

2.4 Gaps Addressed by AES
No prior work provides a unified certification hierarchy (Bronze/Silver/Gold) with formal guarantees covering both deterministic and probabilistic agents, blast radius analysis, and compositional verification. AES fills this gap.

