Chapter 4: Formal Model of the AES Agent

4.1 Agent State
Let an agent $a$ be associated with a state $s \in S$ where
$S = \mathcal{I} \times \mathcal{M} \times \mathcal{L} \times \mathcal{P}_{\text{fin}}(Goals) \times \mathcal{P}_{\text{fin}}(Constraints) \times \mathcal{H}$.

Because $\mathcal{L}$ can be arbitrarily large, $S$ is infinite. To enable finite‑state verification, we use predicate abstraction (Section 4.3).

4.2 Lifecycle as a Transition System
The agent’s execution proceeds through five phases:

1. $s \xrightarrow{\text{perceive}} s'$
2. $s \xrightarrow{\text{update}} s'$
3. $s \xrightarrow{\text{plan}} s'$
4. $s \xrightarrow{\text{act}} s'$
5. $s \xrightarrow{\text{learn}} s'$

For deterministic agents, the transitions are functions. For stochastic agents (LLM‑based), each phase may induce a distribution over next states; we model this as an MDP.

4.3 Predicate Abstraction
Let $\Pi = \{\pi_1, \dots, \pi_m\}$ be a finite set of predicates over $S$ such that for each $p \in AP$ there exists $\pi_p \in \Pi$ with $s \models p \iff \pi_p(s)$. Define $\alpha(s) = \{\pi \in \Pi \mid \pi(s)\}$ and $\gamma(\bar{s}) = \{ s \mid \alpha(s) \subseteq \bar{s} \}$.

The abstract transition system $\overline{T}_a$ has states $\overline{S} = 2^\Pi$ and transitions $\bar{s} \xrightarrow{\alpha} \bar{s}'$ if there exist $s \in \gamma(\bar{s})$, $s' \in \gamma(\bar{s}')$ with $s \xrightarrow{\alpha} s'$.

Theorem 1 (Soundness of Abstraction). If every run of $\overline{T}_a$ satisfies an LTL formula $\varphi$ over $AP$, then every run of $T_a$ satisfies $\varphi$.

Proof. Suppose a concrete run $\rho$ violates $\varphi$. Its projection $\alpha(\rho)$ is an abstract run (by construction) with identical $AP$ labeling, hence also violates $\varphi$. Contrapositively, if all abstract runs satisfy $\varphi$, so do all concrete runs. ∎

4.4 LTL Specifications for Deterministic Compliance

Definition 1 (Fairness Assumption). An execution trace satisfies the fairness assumption $\mathsf{Fair}$ if it obeys $\mathsf{G}(p_{\text{in}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F} p_{\text{res}})$.

Definition 2 (Bronze Compliance – Deterministic). A deterministic agent is Bronze‑compliant if, under the fairness assumption, its traces satisfy:

1. Liveness:
      $\varphi_{\text{live}} \equiv \mathsf{G}\bigl( p_{\text{in}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F}^{\le k}( p_{\text{obs}} \land \mathsf{F}^{\le k}( p_{\text{plan}} \land \mathsf{F}^{\le k}( p_{\text{act}} \land \mathsf{F}^{\le k} p_{\text{learn}} ) ) ) \bigr)$
2. Safety: $\varphi_{\text{safe}} \equiv \mathsf{G}( p_{\text{error}} \rightarrow \mathsf{X}( p_{\text{learn}} \lor \neg p_{\text{error}} ) )$
3. Progress: $\varphi_{\text{prog}} \equiv \mathsf{G}( p_{\text{goals}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F} p_{\text{plan}} )$
4. No deadlock: $\varphi_{\text{dead}} \equiv \mathsf{G}( p_{\text{plan}} \rightarrow ( p_{\text{plan}} \mathsf{U} ( p_{\text{act}} \lor p_{\text{learn}} ) ) )$

Theorem 2 (Correctness with Fairness). For a deterministic, phase‑ordered agent, the four formulas hold under the fairness assumption iff:

· (i) whenever resources are available, each input completes a full cycle within $4k$ steps,
· (ii) errors are transient,
· (iii) goals eventually lead to a plan,
· (iv) no plan remains pending forever.

Proof. ($\Rightarrow$) Direct from LTL semantics. ($\Leftarrow$) Assume fairness. If a trace satisfies (i)–(iv), we construct a proof by induction on the number of inputs. The key step uses fairness to guarantee that once an input arrives, the agent eventually gets resources to progress through the phases, ensuring that the nested bounded chain is satisfied. The other formulas are independent of resources. ∎

