Appendix A: Mathematical Foundations

A.1 Set Theory and Relations

A set is a collection of distinct objects. The cardinality of a finite set X is denoted |X|. The power set of X is 2^X = \{ Y \mid Y \subseteq X \}. A binary relation R \subseteq X \times Y is a set of ordered pairs. A function f: X \to Y is a relation where each x \in X is paired with exactly one y \in Y.

A.2 Partial Orders and Lattices

A partial order (P, \le) is a set with a reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive relation. A lattice is a partial order where every pair of elements has a least upper bound (join) and greatest lower bound (meet). In this work, the health state lattice \mathcal{H} is a finite chain, which is a distributive lattice.

Definition A.1 (Galois Connection). Let (P, \le) and (Q, \sqsubseteq) be partially ordered sets. A pair of functions f: P \to Q and g: Q \to P form a Galois connection if for all p \in P, q \in Q:

f(p) \sqsubseteq q \iff p \le g(q).

In our framework, the certification function \mathsf{certify}: \mathcal{H} \to \mathcal{C} is the lower adjoint of a Galois connection with the “maximal safe abstraction” function.

A.3 Probability Theory

A probability space is a triple (\Omega, \mathcal{F}, \mathbb{P}) where \Omega is the sample space, \mathcal{F} a \sigma-algebra, and \mathbb{P} a probability measure. For a finite set X, a probability distribution is a function \mu: X \to [0,1] with \sum_{x \in X} \mu(x) = 1.

Hoeffding’s Inequality. Let X_1, \dots, X_n be independent random variables with a_i \le X_i \le b_i almost surely. Then for any t > 0,

\mathbb{P}\left( \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (X_i - \mathbb{E}[X_i]) \ge t \right) \le \exp\left( -\frac{2 n^2 t^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n (b_i - a_i)^2} \right).

In our hysteresis monitor, each X_i \in \{0,1\}, so b_i - a_i = 1.

A.4 Linear Temporal Logic (LTL) Semantics

Let \sigma = \sigma_0 \sigma_1 \sigma_2 \dots be an infinite word over 2^{AP}. The satisfaction relation \sigma, i \models \varphi is defined inductively:

· \sigma, i \models p iff p \in \sigma_i.
· \sigma, i \models \neg \varphi iff \sigma, i \not\models \varphi.
· \sigma, i \models \varphi_1 \land \varphi_2 iff \sigma, i \models \varphi_1 and \sigma, i \models \varphi_2.
· \sigma, i \models \mathsf{X} \varphi iff \sigma, i+1 \models \varphi.
· \sigma, i \models \varphi_1 \mathsf{U} \varphi_2 iff there exists j \ge i such that \sigma, j \models \varphi_2 and for all i \le k < j, \sigma, k \models \varphi_1.
· \mathsf{F} \varphi \equiv \top \mathsf{U} \varphi, \mathsf{G} \varphi \equiv \neg \mathsf{F} \neg \varphi.

Bounded operators: \mathsf{F}^{\le k} \varphi means there exists j with i \le j \le i+k such that \sigma, j \models \varphi. This can be expressed using \mathsf{U} with a counter.

A.5 Probabilistic LTL (PCTL)

PCTL formulas are defined over MDPs. State formulas \Phi are:

· \Phi ::= \mathsf{true} \mid p \mid \neg \Phi \mid \Phi \land \Phi \mid \mathbb{P}_{\bowtie p}[\psi] where \psi is a path formula.
· Path formulas: \psi ::= \mathsf{X} \Phi \mid \Phi \mathsf{U}^{\le k} \Phi.

The semantics for MDP \mathcal{M} and policy \pi is given by the probability measure over paths. \mathcal{M}, s \models \mathbb{P}_{\bowtie p}[\psi] iff the probability, under the maximal (or minimal) policy, that paths starting at s satisfy \psi is \bowtie p.

