Appendix B: Detailed Proofs of Theorems

B.1 Proof of Theorem 1 (Soundness of Abstraction)

Theorem. If every run of \overline{T}_a satisfies an LTL formula \varphi over AP, then every run of T_a satisfies \varphi.

Proof. Let \rho = s_0 s_1 s_2 \dots be a concrete run of T_a. Define the abstract run \overline{\rho} = \alpha(s_0) \alpha(s_1) \alpha(s_2) \dots. By construction, for each i, the labeling of \alpha(s_i) with atomic propositions is identical to that of s_i because the predicates \Pi include those that define the propositions. Therefore, \rho \models \varphi iff \overline{\rho} \models \varphi. If \rho violated \varphi, then \overline{\rho} would also violate \varphi, contradicting the assumption that all abstract runs satisfy \varphi. Hence no concrete run can violate \varphi. ∎

B.2 Proof of Theorem 2 (Correctness with Fairness)

Theorem. For a deterministic, phase‑ordered agent, the four formulas hold under the fairness assumption iff (i) whenever resources are available, each input completes a full cycle within 4k steps, (ii) errors are transient, (iii) goals eventually lead to a plan, (iv) no plan remains pending forever.

Proof.
(\Rightarrow) Assume the formulas hold. From \varphi_{\text{live}}, whenever an input occurs and resources are eventually available (by fairness), the nested bounded chain forces each phase to occur within k steps of the previous one, thus within 4k total. Condition (ii) follows from \varphi_{\text{safe}}: if an error occurs, the next state must either be learning or not error; by induction errors cannot persist. (iii) follows from \varphi_{\text{prog}}. (iv) follows from \varphi_{\text{dead}}: a plan cannot stay forever without action or learning.

(\Leftarrow) Assume (i)–(iv) and fairness. We prove by induction on the number of inputs that the trace satisfies each formula. Consider a trace that respects the cycle condition. For \varphi_{\text{live}}, take any occurrence of p_{\text{in}}. By fairness, p_{\text{res}} eventually becomes true, and then by (i) the agent goes through the phases within the deadlines; the nested bounded operators hold. For \varphi_{\text{safe}}, if p_{\text{error}} holds, condition (ii) guarantees that the next state is either learning or not error, satisfying the formula. For \varphi_{\text{prog}}, if goals are present, condition (iii) ensures a plan appears eventually. For \varphi_{\text{dead}}, if a plan exists, condition (iv) ensures it is followed by action or learning, satisfying the until condition. ∎

B.3 Proof of Theorem 3 (CEGAR Soundness and Completeness)

Theorem. For a finite‑state concrete system (or a system with a finite bisimulation quotient), the CEGAR loop terminates with a set of predicates \Pi^* such that \overline{T}_a(\Pi^*) is bisimilar to the concrete system with respect to AP. Consequently, an AES property holds in the concrete system iff it holds in \overline{T}_a(\Pi^*).

Proof. Since the concrete system has a finite bisimulation quotient, there are only finitely many equivalence classes of states distinguishable by AP and by the transition structure. Each refinement step adds a predicate that distinguishes two concrete states that were previously identified in the abstraction. The number of possible refinements is bounded by the number of distinct subsets of the bisimulation quotient, which is finite. Hence termination.

When the abstraction is exact (no spurious transitions), the abstract state space is a partition of the concrete state space into equivalence classes that preserve the labeling and the transition relation. Therefore, the abstract system is bisimilar to the concrete system. Bisimilarity preserves LTL properties (since LTL is bisimulation‑invariant over infinite traces). ∎

B.4 Proof of Theorem 4 (Hysteresis Correctness)

Theorem. For any n, \gamma > 0, the monitor with hysteresis guarantees that the probability of erroneously flagging a violation for a compliant agent is at most e^{-2n\gamma^2}. Moreover, if the true violation probability exceeds \epsilon + \gamma for a contiguous block of n steps, the monitor will output violation within n steps with probability 1.

Proof. Let the true violation probability p \le \epsilon when the agent is compliant. For each step i, define X_i as the indicator of violation at that step. The empirical average Z_t over the window is a sum of independent (or at least bounded) random variables. By Hoeffding’s inequality,

\mathbb{P}[Z_t > \epsilon + \gamma] \le \mathbb{P}[Z_t - p > \gamma] \le e^{-2n\gamma^2}.

Thus the probability that any window triggers a violation when the agent is compliant is bounded by this exponential.

If the true violation probability exceeds \epsilon + \gamma for a contiguous block of length n, then for every window completely contained in that block, the empirical average will be at least \epsilon + \gamma (since all X_i = 1 in that block). Hence the monitor will detect violation within n steps. ∎

B.5 Proof of Theorem 5 (Safety under Degradation)

Theorem. For an agent satisfying the AES compliance formulas for a given health state h, if its health degrades to h' \preceq h, then the agent remains compliant at the certification level \mathsf{certify}(h'), provided it continues to satisfy the same LTL formulas (with the appropriate health‑related atomic propositions).

Proof. Monotonicity of \mathsf{certify} gives \mathsf{certify}(h') \le \mathsf{certify}(h). The LTL formulas for lower certification levels are either identical or weaker (e.g., the bounded liveness deadlines may be larger, or safety properties may be relaxed). Since the agent’s behavior under degraded health is a subset of its possible behaviors under the higher health (it may have fewer capabilities), any trace that satisfied the higher‑tier formulas will also satisfy the lower‑tier formulas. The health‑related propositions are updated accordingly; the formulas referencing them will still hold because the health state is correctly reflected. ∎

B.6 Proof of Theorem 6 (Monitor Correctness under Fairness)

Theorem. Let \sigma be an infinite trace. Define the monitor M with frozen timers as described. Then:

· If M outputs \bot at position i, then there exists a fairness‑satisfying extension of \sigma[0..i] that violates \varphi_{\text{live}}.
· If M outputs \top at position i, then every fairness‑satisfying extension satisfies \varphi_{\text{live}}.
· Otherwise, the verdict is \top_p (pending satisfaction) or \bot_p (pending violation).

Proof. We prove by induction on the prefix length. The monitor state consists of a queue of timers. Each timer corresponds to an input that has been seen but not yet fully processed. The counters track the remaining steps allowed for each phase.

Base case: empty prefix. The queue is empty, verdict \top_p. The future may yet violate, so pending satisfaction is correct.

Inductive step: assume the statement holds for prefixes of length i. Consider prefix \sigma[0..i+1]. The transition of M is deterministic based on the propositions at position i+1 and the current monitor state.

· If the monitor outputs \bot at step i+1, it means that a timer expired (reached zero) while p_{\text{res}} was true at some earlier step. At that moment, the agent had sufficient resources but failed to complete the phase within the allowed steps. No fairness‑satisfying extension can later recover that input’s chain because the bounded deadline has been missed permanently. Hence there exists an extension (in fact, any extension) that violates \varphi_{\text{live}}. The output \bot is correct.
· If the monitor outputs \top at step i+1, the queue has become empty. This means all previously pending inputs have completed all phases. Any future input does not affect the satisfaction of the formula for those completed inputs. Moreover, the formula \varphi_{\text{live}} only requires that each input eventually completes its chain; it does not impose further constraints after completion. Therefore, every extension satisfies \varphi_{\text{live}}, and \top is correct.
· If the verdict is pending, the monitor’s internal state reflects that no deadline has been missed and the queue is not empty. There exist both extensions that eventually satisfy and extensions that eventually violate (by, e.g., delaying further phases). The pending verdict is therefore correct.

The induction holds. ∎

B.7 Proof of Theorem 7 (Trust‑Weighted Compositional Correctness)

Theorem. Under the acyclic ordering and the trust‑based assumptions, if for every agent a we have A_a \models G_a, then the composition of all agents satisfies \bigwedge_a G_a even in the presence of non‑certified agents, provided Gold agents exercise their refusal primitive.

Proof. By induction on the order. Let the agents be ordered a_1, a_2, \dots, a_N such that the assumptions of a_i only mention agents a_j with j < i. For the base case, agents with no inputs (order 0) have assumptions \top and we have G_{a_0} by hypothesis.

Assume that for all agents of order < i, the composition satisfies their guarantees. Consider agent a_i. Its assumptions A_{a_i} refer only to agents of lower order, which by induction satisfy their guarantees. Moreover, for any non‑certified agent b that a_i interacts with, if b’s certification is below the trust level required by a_i, the refusal primitive discards inputs from b that do not satisfy a safety predicate. This ensures that the environment seen by a_i satisfies the preconditions of A_{a_i} (since any unsafe input is filtered out). Hence the environment of a_i satisfies A_{a_i}, and by the local proof, a_i satisfies G_{a_i}.

Thus all agents satisfy their guarantees, and the composition satisfies \bigwedge_a G_a. ∎

