Appendix C: CEGAR Details

C.1 Predicate Discovery via Interpolation

Given a spurious counterexample \overline{\rho} = \bar{s}_0 \bar{s}_1 \dots \bar{s}_n, we need to find a new predicate \pi that eliminates the spurious transition. Let i be an index where the transition from \bar{s}_i to \bar{s}_{i+1} is infeasible. The sets Pre = \gamma(\bar{s}_i) and Post = Post(\gamma(\bar{s}_i)) are sets of concrete states. Since the transition is spurious, \gamma(\bar{s}_{i+1}) \cap Post = \emptyset.

We compute a predicate \pi such that:

· For all s \in \gamma(\bar{s}_i), \pi(s) is true.
· For all s \in Post, \pi(s) is false.
  This can be done using Craig interpolation in the theory of linear arithmetic or bit‑vectors, depending on the system’s data types. Adding \pi to \Pi will split \bar{s}_i into two abstract states, making the spurious transition disappear.

C.2 SMT‑Based Concretization Check

To check if a counterexample trace \overline{\rho} is spurious, we construct a formula:

\Phi = \bigwedge_{t=0}^{n-1} \bigl( \bigwedge_{\pi \in \bar{s}_t} \pi(x_t) \land \bigwedge_{\pi \notin \bar{s}_t} \neg \pi(x_t) \bigr) \land \bigwedge_{t=0}^{n-1} \textit{Trans}(x_t, x_{t+1}),

where \textit{Trans}(x_t, x_{t+1}) encodes the concrete transition relation. If \Phi is satisfiable, the trace is concrete; otherwise it is spurious.

