Appendix D: Probabilistic Model Checking and PCTL Semantics

D.1 PCTL Semantics over MDPs

Let \mathcal{M} = (S, Act, P, s_0) be an MDP. A policy \pi resolves nondeterminism. The probability measure \mathbb{P}_{\mathcal{M}, \pi} over infinite paths is defined in the standard way. For a path formula \psi, the satisfaction set Paths(\mathcal{M}, \pi, \psi) is measurable. For a state s and a policy \pi, we write \mathbb{P}_{\mathcal{M}, \pi}(s \models \psi) for the probability that a path starting from s under \pi satisfies \psi.

Definition D.1 (PCTL Semantics). For an MDP \mathcal{M}, a state s, and a PCTL state formula \Phi:

· \mathcal{M}, s \models p iff p \in L(s).
· \mathcal{M}, s \models \neg \Phi iff \mathcal{M}, s \not\models \Phi.
· \mathcal{M}, s \models \Phi_1 \land \Phi_2 iff \mathcal{M}, s \models \Phi_1 and \mathcal{M}, s \models \Phi_2.
· \mathcal{M}, s \models \mathbb{P}_{\bowtie p}[\psi] iff for all (or for some, depending on interpretation) policies \pi, \mathbb{P}_{\mathcal{M}, \pi}(s \models \psi) \bowtie p.

For our probabilistic Bronze, we use the existential interpretation (under the actual policy), but the abstraction must be sound for that interpretation.

D.2 Abstraction for Probabilistic Verification

Given an MDP \mathcal{M} and a set of predicates \Pi, we build an abstract MDP \overline{\mathcal{M}} where each abstract state \bar{s} corresponds to a set of concrete states. The transition probabilities are over‑approximated: for each action a, the probability to go from \bar{s} to \bar{s}' is the maximum probability over concrete states in \bar{s} of reaching \bar{s}' in one step. This yields an MDP that is a probabilistic simulation of the concrete one. If a PCTL lower‑bound property holds in the abstraction, it holds in the concrete system; for upper‑bound properties, one uses minimum probabilities.

