Appendix G: Design Patterns for AES‑Compliant Agents

G.1 Phase Separation Pattern

Agents must clearly separate the five phases. A common design pattern is to have a central scheduler that invokes distinct modules for perception, update, planning, action, and learning. Each module is stateless except for the shared agent state. This makes it easy to monitor the phase transitions.

G.2 Resource Monitoring Pattern

To support the fairness condition, agents should expose a resource availability predicate p_{\text{res}}. This can be implemented by monitoring CPU load, network latency, or by checking a “throttle” flag set by the host system. The monitor uses this to freeze timers appropriately.

G.3 Degradation Wrapper

A degradation wrapper encapsulates the agent and intercepts all sensor inputs. It evaluates diagnostic predicates (Table 7.1) and updates the health state. When the health changes, it injects the new health proposition into the monitor and may adjust the agent’s operational parameters (e.g., speed limits) to match the lower certification tier.

G.4 Refusal Filter for Trust

For Gold agents that need to interoperate with untrusted peers, a refusal filter is placed in front of the perception module. It validates each incoming message against a safety predicate; if validation fails, the message is dropped and p_{\text{in}} is not raised for that input. This ensures that the agent’s state update only processes trusted information.